node.text: Posting this to distract myself
For you, from me 🌹
The best present. ❤️

My whole adult life I’ve heard “follow your intuition”. But when anxiety entered the equation for me I found it hard differentiating the two. Because anxiety had a lot of the same characteristics as intuition (or so I thought) I found myself holding onto the anxiety even more, fearing it was an inner voice that was giving me some sort of truth.

Therapy and research helped me begin to see and feel the difference. And distinguishing the two is what finally helped me to let go of the attachment to my anxious thoughts.

Disclaimer: *I am not a licensed therapist/ psychologist. My explanations are simply based on my personal experiences.*

In the midst of my journey with WNRS there’s so many blessings, fun, and growth. There’s also mistakes, challenges, and fear. I always try and remind myself that it’s all part of the journey, especially the uncomfortable moments.

Instead of punishing myself for the let downs and mistakes, I try to refocus that energy to remember that the fact that I’m even getting to work on something I’m so passionate about everyday is a blessing, regardless of the struggles that day.

I’ve been in relationships where I was more interested in my idea of the person than the reality. They’d show me who they were but when that didn’t fit my ideal, I’d ignore it. Then, i’d feel hurt in the process wondering why they kept letting me down, not realizing I was hurting myself pretending they were something they weren’t.

I always try and remind myself that even in a painful experience/ interaction, it’s happening FOR me never to me. Finding the lesson in every experience keeps feeling empowered even when I’m feeling beat down.
